{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[2]", "headings": "['Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample']"}, "page_content": "Population Synthesis Using Incomplete Microsample\nTo address data collection challenges, researchers developed population synthesis algorithms to create synthetic populations. They provide ABM transport models with a reliable alternative to actual population data. Population synthesis techniques generate a comprehensive list of synthetic populations, each accompanied by corresponding attribute data. The objective of population synthesis is to optimally utilize the existing microsamples, along with the additional aggregated marginal information on each attribute of interest, in order to generate agents that closely align with the underlying population structure (Sun and Erath (2015)). These simulated agents can thereafter be used to evaluate governmental policies in the region or conduct studies that would be prohibitively costly, ethically questionable, or just unfeasible using actual population data.", "type": "Document"}}